2026-04-16 12:15:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load-module series diode'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU is supplying a solid 12 V and its indicator LED is on, so the source and polarity are correct. There is no polarity inversion in the cabling, as verified by continuity/voltage tests, and the inverted-cable indicator LED in the control module remains off. Measurements show that the control module’s output ‘+’ line sits at only about +0.36 V relative to 0 V, and in the load module the anode of the series diode is at ~0.36 V while its cathode and both lamp terminals are at 0 V. That is exactly the behavior of a forward‑biased silicon diode clamping the line: it is conducting and pulling the upstream node down to ground instead of passing the supply through to the lamps. This means the diode has failed short (or partially short) to ground rather than blocking in reverse and conducting only when the correct polarity and supply are present. Because this diode is in series with both lamps, its short‑to‑ground failure prevents any significant voltage appearing across the lamps, so neither the main lamp nor the indicator lamp can turn on even though the rest of the system wiring and control circuitry are correct. Replacing the faulty series diode in the load module should restore proper lamp operation.'
