2026-04-16 12:16:18 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control-module switch', 'wiring/trace between switch output terminal and control output (+) line'] hypothesis_explanation='The measurements show ~12 V at the control-module input (+) and at the switch input terminal, but only ~0.36 V at the switch output terminal and on the control output (+) line, even when the switch is closed. Downstream, the anode of the load-module diode also sits at ~0.36 V while the rest of the load branch is at 0 V. This indicates that the only significant voltage drop in the path from the PSU to the load is occurring across the switch (and/or its immediate output connection), behaving as an open or very high-resistance element rather than a low-resistance closed contact. The power module and polarity are confirmed good, and the load-module diode and lamps are not faulty (replacement of the diode had no effect and there is essentially no current through the load). Therefore the most plausible root cause is a failed or poorly connected control-module switch contact, or a cracked/open PCB trace or joint between the switch output terminal and the control-module output (+) cable. Repairing or replacing the switch and its output connection should restore full 12 V to the load when the switch is operated.'
